What a heavy fucking week. 

Cheers to being my my homie. My dude that lived up the street. The dude I called my friend. The one that called me Juice. 

Cheers to all the ruckus we caused and all the good you did. Cheers to your amazing smile and cheers to your amazing food. I miss the simpler times. Bombing hills head first into cattle fences. Buying my old broken cars when you thought I was too stupid to fix them. To long rides and not needing to say a word. An understanding without all the bullshit. 

Cheers to painting my house, celebrating records and the count down til cars break. Cheers to making wood and to visiting when shit got too fake. 

Cheers to your amazing wife and wonderful family. Cheers to you finding your light, to knowing your worth and that you were the only Dawg.

I often think about how our lives would have been different if that night hadn’t been so fucked. If you didn’t feel you had to carry all the weight. I wish we could have shared some more adventures. Some more fires full of lies and safer knives. I loved you then and I love you now. 

Be easy my dude. I’ll see you on the other side.

Fun splash at my favorite place in the world the other day. Easy ride on flat seas. Welcomed by that good blue blue with infinite vis. How far? Who knows, who cares? 

The best time of year here in Monterey. Always hard to pull away from it but was nice to meet the hula skirt siphonophore (second image) to prep for the real deal and whales soon. Hopefully we can snag a bit more of this before Maui. 

If you’re in town. Go diving.

Happy holidays my friends! No snow in sight here, but plenty of you are thick in it. 

Thinking back on a fun dive with @waittfoundation off Saba Bank where the snow was plentiful and jellies waltz. 

#snow #holidays #christmas

Very excited to be migrating back to Maui for our annual winter with whales  to document humpback research and behavior with @whaletrustmaui.

Can’t wait to reunite with the whole whale family community. 

First image by @flipnicklin. Second by Jason Sturgis. Both under NMFS permit # 19225

We spend a lot of time looking at whales and sometimes they look back. 

This female, accompanied by her male escort, was fascinated with our prop. She’d swim right up to it, invert and seemingly stare at it. The male, being a male, would get impatient. Blast her with  bubbles to move her along. In the case he could move her, she would quickly return. This “friendly” activity went on for over two hours with this group. 

Fascinating day with @whaletrustmaui.
#image take. Under NMFS permit # 19225

A smaller pup rides the back of a larger pup during a play date in Monterey, CA. 

Lacking blubber, otters are often living on the brink of survival. To compensate, the otters spend their days resting or voraciously feeding.  Requiring up to 30% of their body weight in food per day. 

The demands of being a mother push females even further. Females have come up with a solution in the form of pup play dates. While the youngins get out their extra energy, mothers dive constantly to collect their much needed extra calories.  While having seen this behavior from surface, I often wondered what they were up to down there. Never would I have thought they were giving one another rides. 

Shot for @natgeo for the feb issue with the amazing @kiliiiyuyan and @chamiltonjames . The online issue is now available. 

Special thanks to all the people in Monterey that made it possible and all the friends that helped fix my gear when it broke in the hostile environments otters love to call home. 

Photos taken under FWS permit # 37946D

Happy days here on maui. Plenty of sunshine and plenty of whales. Good week of productive science and interesting whales. When you can’t back up or zoom out any more. Shot full frame at 10.5 mm equivalent. 

Working with @whaletrustmaui under NMFS permit # 25987

Nothing but rain for days around here. Thinking back on some happy days. 

4 species of sharks, tuna, rainbow runners and dolphins smash a bait ball. Over thousand large predators doing what they do best on a school of scad. 

#sharks #baitball #sharks #tuna

As young kids growing up in the mountains these yellow borders were our transport to the far off corners of the world. I had no aspirations to ever be a photographer and may have have not even known what an otter was. 

It’s incredibly cool to see a story I worked on with the amazing @kiliiiyuyan and @chamiltonjames on sea otters for this months @natgeo magazine. All while working in my home town. 

Otters are incredible and capable animals. Far more complex than their often described cuteness. And if we dont respect them for what they truly are, how can we ever manage them correctly. Many thanks to all the scientists and friends that have helped me along the way. 

All CA images taken under NMFS permit # 37946D

A southern sea otter (Enhydra lutris) pup collects mussels on a shallow mussel bed with her mother in Monterey, CA. 

Although otters are feeding generalists, individuals will often specialize on particular prey. This is generally learned from their mother in the first few months of their life. In addition having to teach how to hunt, mothers also have to teach youngsters how to swim, where to hunt, how to groom,etc. Six short and formative months to teach their kin how to survive and thrive in a wild and harsh world. 

Shot for a @natgeo story “What’s not to love,” published Feb ‘23. A pandemic baby that took a village to complete with all the restrictions in place. @kiliiiyuyan covered the Alaska portion of the story documenting a population explosion, what that looks like for humans who make a living on the same food sources and what it looks like to share after conservation. I covered down here in California where the story is a bit different as the population is having a much harder time rebounding. Additional images provided by @chamiltonjames. Magnificent and dreamy words provided  by the wonderful @cynthiagorney. 

Image take. Under US FWS permit # 37946D

If only for a moment, a juvenile sea otter pauses in her mighty kingdom of Monterey, CA. 

As a member of the weasel family (Mustelidae), sea otters lack fat storage and must rely on their fur (the densest in the animal kingdom) and a fast metabolism. To feed their metabolism sea otters must eat up to 30% of their body weight a day. 

Like other weasels, sea otters are quite smart and can be rather mischievous. Still moments are rare. Catching the reflection of his own self on the dome of my underwater housing, this youngster paused for a moment before carrying on with his daily duties.

After swimming what felt like two miles in cold, dark and poor vis water I finally something to photograph. Back to the land of Monterey on a bad day. The buzzing sea lions, friendly harbor seals… just too far away in dismal vis. 

I finally found a shy little tubesnout (2nd frame) dashing in and out of the kelp. It slowly made his way to check in on these eggs. Not sure any were his/hers but glad she led the way. 

Two hours in the cold reminded me why I bought a dry suit. Should have used it.

On a shallow mussel bed in Monterey, CA, a southern sea otter makes a dive to find some food. 

Sea otters need to eat roughly 30% their weight in food per day. This high calorie diet feeds their high metabolic rate. Lacking blubber storage like other marine mammals, they rely on heat from digestion and that million hair per inch coat of theirs to keep them alive. 30% of my body weight per day in Big Macs is a staggering 120, roughly. Imagine how awful that would be.

A southern sea otter dives below an 8 ft wave in monterey, CA. 

For an otter, an 8 ft wave isnt much to slow it down. I’ve seen them working much shallower on 20 ft swell days. 

But, for humans this is quite the hostile environment. The area the otter is going to work is considerably shallower. Have I gone in there in these conditions, yes. Should I have, maybe not. The shallower you go, the stronger the surge. The shallower you go, the less room you have to escape. Each new wave pushes more water into the shallows. But, what goes in must come out. The bubbly foam water quickly approaches zero ft vis. Not a good scenario when you are about to be pulled 70 meters out over boulders. Not a good scenario when you are carrying valuable glass. But worth it to get situations like the previous post. 

Otters are incredibly capable animals. Ones that play on days we go home. Working these shallow reefs was much different than working kelp areas. Much more big wave photography than underwater photography. These zones proved to cost thousands in damages. But, proved to create some wonderful and crazy memories. 

US FWS permit # 37946D

A female southern sea otter and her pup search for food in the kelp forests of Monterey, CA. 

After searching the blades (think leaves) in the canopy they will descend the frond (whole plant) checking the whole stipe to the bottom where they will even examine the holdfasts (think roots) for snails and crabs. Once on the bottom they zoom off to another nearby frond but not before checking the rocks and sand for abalone, urchins, octos, innkeeper worms and even sand dollars in particular months. These early months are important for the pups as they need to learn what is good to eat, where to find it and how to open it. 

Hard work keeping up with these kelp scavenging otters. It’s not uncommon to swim a half mile or mile trying to be in a spot where you might be able to make a frame. 

Image taken under US FWS permit # 37946D for a @natgeo mag story that came out in February.

Witnessing Conservation: Southern California green turtles. 

Green turtle populations have been present in the SoCal region for ages. Numbers started to dwindle due to high fishing pressures and nests being sacked on their nesting beaches. Conservationists have been working for decades to bring the iconic turtles back. One of the first places (in the 1980s) that turtles were being seen again was in the South Bay at the warm water outflow of the power plant. Allowing them to feed throughout the year due to the warm eater and grow at nearly twice the rate of any other green turtle at the same latitude. Images taken with the NOAA turtle crew under NMFS permit # 16803
Banded guitarshark (Zapteryx exasperata) in a lovely bed of eelgrass.

Golden hour with a turtle friend a few years back in San Diego, CA. 

Sure do love these uptown queens hanging around on the posh reefs of La Jolla.
Lil while back the whole 20 miles across monterey bay was choke full of these golden orbs. Hoping they return soon.

We spend a whole lot of time researching/looking at whales and occasionally they show some interest in looking at us. when they do, you just hope they know what they are doing. Being a foot away means you are no longer in control. 

Although they are often called gentle giants, let’s not forget F=MA. They may not be accelerating much, but there is a whole lot of mass behind this lady and that equates to a whole lot of force. 

I often get asked my favorite animal to work with. There are many but there sure is something special about large and intelligent animals  animals seeking connection. 

With @whaletrustmaui under NMFS permit # 25987

Leatherback sea turtle Monterey Bay, CA.  2020

During a pandemic, underwater photographers are not deemed the most essentials workers. With plenty of time on my hands, I spent a lot of time off shore. At the time there had been loads of jellies in the bay. I went back to a place I was the previous day but the jellies slide down hill with the current. The water was extremely dirty and everything but the top 6 inches or so was a red tide algal bloom. I turned off the boat and was having lunch when I heard something breathe right next to the boat. When I turned around there was a massive leatherback. 

I quickly grabbed my camera and dipped it over the side (sans strobes unfortunately) and rattled off a few frames. 

After so many years working with turtles it was wonderful to finally see a leatherback in the water in my home town. There are a lot better places to photograph them with good vis, but to my knowledge I have not ever seen another underwater photo of one off the west coast of US. If you’ve heard of one, I’d love to hear about it. 

Hope to see more again this year.
A spade flush. In the chaos of a school of spade fish, three line up for a brief moment. Hard to beat a spade flush. Taken with @hiimjoe88 while working in the Gulf of Mexico last week.

I always welcome new experiences and this was certainly a first. But, a bit strange I must say. We had planned a dive but after descending and having less than 2 ft of vis we aborted. I took off the gear and was shooting images on the snorkel  when I kicked something. No luck sorting out it was and then that 2 ft something quickly shot up my shorts, did a few laps around before shooting the gap of a butt crack created hole on the backside. 

I’m all for the funky and strange but this one was a bit concerning at the moment. Zero vis and things zooming and wrapping all around on the inside of the shorts. 

After this shark sucker exited and I was able to identify it, we both calmed the nerves and  she made her self at home on my leg for a while and I was able to get a photo (video on second slide). 

She shortly wanted to seek shade and resume uncomfortable behaviors.  I felt it might be time to get out. 

I’m just glad the video wasn’t rolling for the first bit

Large surf on these shallow reefs have little to no impact on foraging behavior. It obviously has  a much larger impact on photography equipment.

Blue rockfish swarm above a pinnacle in monterey bay, ca. 

With the loss of kelp, it’s quite strange finding schools of fish that typically aggregate in the missing canopies. 

As if they were lost, the fish followed along as if I could be some kind of structure for them to seek refuge under.

I was recently asked about this image and how it might print for a fundraiser. I had never printed it before but happy to say @bradleyprintservices tested it yesterday and it looks wonderful. 

Single exposure from Cuba a few years back with @octavioaburto, @claudio_contreras_koob and @ben.fiscella doing some science things.

Hey friends! 

Happy to announce an exhibit I have called “Kelp Grizzlies” is now up at the @pgmuseum here in Monterey, CA. 30+ images of otters in their underwater world for locals to see they do “stuff” when not bobbing overly cute at the surface. A glimpse, albeit small, into their incredible lives. 

We are doing an opening at @pgmuseum this wed night. You need to register as space is limited. Link in my bio or through the @pgmuseum Instagram or website. A night of wine and otters. 

All the prints were gorgeously printed on archival paper by @bradleyprintservices (the best ) and mounted and glassed by Glenn Gobel Custom Frames. Both local shops that do incredible work. 

I salvaged the wood from a 100 yr old home here in PG that was ripping out their old Doug fir flooring. Lots of nails and lots of milling. I left small non-structural defects to  help tell it’s story and reflect on what can be when given a second life., just like the otters when a small remnant population of 50 were found in 1938 when most thought they were extinct from the fur trade. The walnut frame is from a piece of firewood I found camping in northern ca. 

Not sure if I’ll do another one or what but the prints and frames are all one offs and available for purchase. Mounted, UV acrylic, archival paper and the frame as a package. 

Thanks to everyone that has made it possible. 

All images taken under  NMFS permit # 37946D

A broadbill swordfish (Xiphias gladius) is caught to be satellite tagged off California by researchers at the Pleger Institute of Environmental Research (@pier_research ). Using satellite telemetry, the PIER crew are able to track migrations (daily and yearly) to better understand stocks and populations that inhabit the California waters. Using this information, PIER has developed an alternative gear type, called Deep-set Buoy Gear, that targets swordfish at depth and greatly reduces bycatch while maintaining a high catch rate. California currently has mechanisms in place that are designed to safeguard protected species such as leatherback sea turtles. When turtles are present, the Pacific Leatherback Conservation Area is closed to fishermen that target swordfish. But, in those years the USA consumer does not simply quit eating swordfish, but rather the demand is met by less regulated fisheries from around the world. It was estimated that in 11 years of the conservation area closure some 50 leatherbacks were saved in US waters, but by exporting our fishery some 1500 leatherbacks were killed abroad. Conservation of our resources must be of the highest concern going forward, but only in ways that make the most sense. By using science and common sense we can safeguard our natural resources while also providing a local jobs and a good local product.

I’m thrilled to be part of the @Vital.Impacts fine art print sale with so many wonderful photographers. This image came from one of my first dives with a camera. The sale is in support of Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e), Africa's first indigenous-owned elephant sanctuary. 

Funds raised will send 13 orphaned elephants back to the wild.This moment is such an immense achievement for the sanctuary and their brave young orphans – who arrived with considerable odds stacked against them, and so much to overcome. 

I am honored to support this important moment and highlight the vital link between empowering women, environmental stewardship, and wildlife preservation. 

Learn more and explore all the exquisite works available by visiting bit.ly/vitalimpactssale (link in profile).
